×008B:  hehe  and  what  should  that  suppose to be? :-)
Anyway,  what  is  the  passion with true pixelart to
you?×

S:  There  are  three  main  things,  I  suppose. The
creation,  the   challenge   and   the   competition.

Creativity  is  the  most  important  - it's when the
vision  from  your head wants to become an image. And
then  it's  the  challenge.  How to paint an image in
such  a  limited environment? And finally we have the
competition.  Compete with the other artists - it can
be  a  pleasant  joy  and  motivation for keeping on.

×008B:  A  very  intresting  view!   And  I'm  happy  you
wanted to  share that with us. Since many years,  the
pixelart  is  a  decreasing phenomena at the Amiga as
platform. How should the pixelart survive or increase
in   popularity   again   you   think?×

S: The true pixelart was born because of the hardware
limits.  Now,  the  computers has changed, and so the
scene  has  changed  as well. Now, it's quite hard to
find a graphician who wants to paint the image in 320
x  256  x 8bit, if he can do it in 1024 x 768 x 24bit
without  any  limits.  But, I think that the pixelart
will  survive, because it's still alive. Maybe not on
the  scene,  maybe  not  even  on Amiga scene, but in
mobile  and  console games. And it's again because of
hardware   limits.

